<p>Suppose it is known that a proportion of 0.002 of Dutch women have disease <em>D</em>. There is a test to detect this disease. That test is not always reliable: in 0.04 of the cases in which the person has the disease, the test gives the result “no disease” with a negative result. And 0.96 of them are detected with a positive result. Furthermore: in 0.96 of those who do not have it, the test gives a negative result. Marja is told that she has a negative test result.</p>
<p>Set the events:</p>
<ul>
<li><em>D</em> = The disease <em>D</em>,</li>
<li><em>N</em> = The negative test result.</li>
</ul>
<p>Then what is the probability P(<em>D</em> and <em>N</em>) that Marja gets a negative test result and she also has the disease?</p>
</p>]]></text>
